                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d203">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.512351 Double/237: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-04-04T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 4, 1935—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>119. Your 264, March 29, 11 a.m. I want you to know how fully we appreciate the
                    splendid work you have done in obtaining Parliamentary approval on this treaty.
                    We have received numerous expressions of appreciation from interested American
                    concerns. I am sure you are lending every effort to getting immediate exchange
                    of ratifications, but I do hope that there will not be much more delay in
                    accomplishing such an exchange. The announcement of an exchange of ratifications
                    would certainly create a more favorable attitude here for the reception of the
                    announcement which may be made with regard to intention to negotiate a trade
                    agreement with France.<note n="48" xml:id="d203fn48">See <ref target="#pg_211"
                            >pp. 211</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
